Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[EEE virus is endemic along the Gulf Coast, Eastern Seaboard and as far west as the Upper Midwestern states of the USA. Wild birds are the reservoir hosts, and the black-tailed mosquito, _Culiseta melanura_, is the vector in swamps. Other mosquito species may act as bridge vectors, carrying the virus out of swamps into adjoining localities and transmitting the virus to humans and equine animals. Clinical cases in humans are very serious, with a case fatality rate of 33 per cent and significant neurological sequelae in those who survive the infection (see http://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis). Although human infections are rare, it is prudent to follow the recommendations given above to avoid mosquito bites until killing frosts eliminate mosquito vectors and halt transmission. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3617180,234.]
